06459nam a22009975i 9789048540013DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485400137 a10.1515/97890485400132doi  a(DE-B1597)590760  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aNE625 7aART0480002bisacsh04a769.922300aPrints as Agents of Global Exchange :b1500-1800 /ced. by Heather Madar. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (322 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aVisual and Material Culture, 1300 –1700 ;v3100tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of illustrations -- tIntroduction -- t1 Concealing and Revealing the Female Body in European Prints and Mughal Paintings -- t2 The Sultan’s Face Looks East and West: European Prints and Ottoman Sultan Portraiture -- t3 From Europe to Persia and Back Again : Border-Crossing Prints and the Asymmetries of Early Modern Cultural Encounter -- t4 The Dissemination of Western European Prints Eastward: The Armenian Case -- t5 The Catholic Reformation and Japanese Hidden Christians: Books as Historical Ties -- t6 (Re)framing the Virgin of Guadalupe : The Concurrence of Early Modern Prints and Colonial Devotions in Creating the Virgin -- t7 Hidden Resemblances: Re-contextualized and Re-framed : Diego de Valadés’ Cross Cultural Exchange -- t8 The Practice of Art: Auxiliary Plastic Models and Prints in Italy, Spain, and Peru -- t9 Ink and Feathers: Prints, Printed Books, and Mexican Featherwork -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe significance of the media and communications revolution occasioned by printmaking was profound. Less a part of the standard narrative of printmaking’s significance is recognition of the frequency with which the widespread dissemination of printed works also occurred beyond the borders of Europe and consideration of the impact of this broader movement of printed objects. Within a decade of the invention of the printing press, European prints began to move globally. Over the course of the fifteenth to the eighteenth centuries, numerous prints produced in Europe traveled to areas as varied as Turkey, India, Persia, Ethiopia, China, Japan and the Americas, where they were taken by missionaries, artists, travelers, merchants and diplomats. This collection of essays explores the transmission of knowledge, both written and visual, between Europe and the rest of the world by means of prints in the early modern period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aPrintsxHistory. 0aPrintsxTechniquexHistory. 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aModern History. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aART / Prints.2bisacsh  aPrints, Cross-cultural Exchange, Early Modern.1 aBáez, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarreón, Emilie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallori, Corinna T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMadar, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMadar, Heather, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMerian, Sylvie L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrii, Yoshimi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPreisinger, Raphaèle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRagazzi, Alexandre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmentek, Kristel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaraich, Saleema, econtributor.4ctb4htt